This paper discusses a mechanism to improve the efficiency of cellular networks by leveraging inter-cell device-to-device (D2D) communication. As such, it is likely to fall under the arXiv sub-category of "Networking and Internet Architecture" (cs.NI). Additionally, the paper involves modeling and analysis of the traffic patterns and spectrum requirements, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of "Information Theory" (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the use of D2D communication for load balancing, which could be considered a form of "Social and Information Networks" (cs.SI). Furthermore, the paper evaluates the effectiveness of the proposed mechanism using real-world data traces, which could place it under the sub-category of "Multimedia" (cs.MM) or "Cryptography and Security" (cs.CR) depending on the specific focus of the evaluation.
